Michael Mann is the most overrated director of his generation. Maybe with his latest picture "Public Enemies" people will begin to see how shallow and inept he really is. 

The film is shot using the 'earthquake cam' style of film-making that has been popular with directors for over a decade now. This 'style' of jerky hand-held camera movement should be seen for what it is: poor camera craft. In the case of 'Public Enemies' this gimmickry is a constant sickening distraction. What is wrong with using steady-cam or a tripod? 

There is absolutely no character development in 'Public Enemies'. So why care about anyones fate? The fact that the lead is played by Johnny Depp does not automatically instill empathy.

The history the film tries to depict as raw reality is contrived fiction. 

All in all this is a shoddy mess that should prove without a doubt the serious limitations of Michael Mann as a director.
